            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "The code provided in the file \"fibonacci.py\" implements a recursive solution to compute the Fibonacci sequence for a given input \\( n \\). Here's the explanation:\n\n### Code Explanation:\n```python\ndef fibonacci(n):\n    if n <= 1:\n        return n\n    return fibonacci(n-1) + fibonacci(n-2)\n\nresult = fibonacci(10)\nprint(f\"Fibonacci(10) = {result}\")\n```\n\n1. **Base Cases:** \n   - If \\( n \\) is less than or equal to 1, the function immediately returns \\( n \\). This handles the first two Fibonacci numbers: \\( \\text{Fibonacci}(0) = 0 \\) and \\( \\text{Fibonacci}(1) = 1 \\).\n\n2. **Recursive Calls:**\n   - For \\( n > 1 \\), the function computes \\( \\text{Fibonacci}(n) \\) recursively as:\n     \\[\n     \\text{Fibonacci}(n) = \\text{Fibonacci}(n-1) + \\text{Fibonacci}(n-2)\n     \\]\n     This corresponds to the mathematical definition of the Fibonacci sequence.\n\n3. **Example Execution:**\n   - For \\( n = 10 \\), the computation calls:\n     \\[\n     \\text{Fibonacci}(10) = \\text{Fibonacci}(9) + \\text{Fibonacci}(8)\n     \\]\n     These recursive calls continue until they reach the base cases.\n\n4. The result is printed out as \\( \\text{Fibonacci}(10) = 55 \\).\n\n---\n\n### Computational Complexity:\nThe computational complexity of this recursive implementation is **exponential**, i.e., \\( O(2^n) \\). \n\n- This happens because:\n  - Each call to the `fibonacci` function results in two more calls, leading to exponential growth in the number of computations.\n  - There is no memoization or caching of intermediate results, causing redundant calculations (e.g., \\( \\text{Fibonacci}(5) \\) is computed multiple times).\n\n---\n\n### Efficiency Improvement:\nTo optimize the Fibonacci computation:\n- Use **Dynamic Programming** with memoization to achieve \\( O(n) \\) complexity, or\n- Use an **iterative solution**, which calculates the sequence step by step, also in \\( O(n) \\).",
